]] (an elite military academy he had founded) in 1773, where Schiller eventually studied medicine. The Duke was very demanding of his students, and Schiller's childhood was a lonely and unhappy one, but he was greatly enriched by the excellent education he received. It was there that he wrote his first play, ''[[Die R\u00e4uber]]'' (\"The Robbers\"), about a group of na\u00efve revolutionaries and their tragic failure.\n\n[[Leopold Mozart]] visited W\u00fcrttemberg with his son, [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]] in July 1763 and said, \"Ludwigsburg is a very special town.\"<ref>[http://www.world66.com/europe/germany/badenwrttemberg/ludwigsburg \"Ludwigsburg Travel Guide\"] world66.com Accessed March 4, 2010</ref>\n\n===Present and former residents of Ludwigsburg===\n* [[Ilse Koch]] (1906-1967), the wife of [[Karl-Otto Koch|Karl Koch]] (1897-1945), the commandant of the concentration camps [[Buchenwald]] from 1937 to 1941 and [[Majdanek]] from 1941 to 1943.\n* [[Horst K\u00f6hler]], (born 1943), former Federal President of Germany and previous managing director of the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF) grew up in Ludwigsburg.<ref>[http://www.bundespraesident.de/-,11050/Bundespraesident-Horst-Koehler.htm R\u00e9sum\u00e9 of President Horst K\u00f6hler] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100221180943/http://www.bundespraesident.de/-,11050/Bundespraesident-Horst-Koehler.htm |date=2010-02-21 }} Official presidential website. Retrieved March 2, 2010</ref>\n* [[Hans Scholl]], (1918-1943), German student and member of the Nazi resistance group, the [[White Rose]], executed by the Nazis\n* [[Sophie Scholl]], (1921-1943), German student and member of the Nazi resistance group, the [[White Rose]], executed by the Nazis<ref>[http://www.sophie-scholl-in-ludwigsburg.de/scholl_inlb_en.html Sophie Scholl in Ludwigsburg]. Website about Sophie Scholl's childhood years in Ludwigsburg. Accessed March 4, 2010</ref>\n* [[Friedrich Silcher]] (1789-1860), German composer, wrote music in Ludwigsburg\n[[File:Friedrich Silcher.jpg|thumb|130px|Friedrich Silcher and his wife 1822]]\n* [[Carl Maria von Weber]] (1786-1826), wrote music in Ludwigsburg.\n* [[Eva Heller]], (1948-2008), German author and social scientist, grew up in Ludwigsburg.  She was born in neighboring Esslingen am Neckar.\n<!--\n===Ehrenb\u00fcrger=== -->\n\n===People born in Ludwigsburg===\n* [[Charles Pfizer]] (1824\u20131906), German chemist and founder of [[Pfizer Inc.]]\n* [[Wilhelm Emil Fein]] (1842-1898), German inventor\n* [[Gerold von Gleich]] (1869-1938), German army officer, military memoirist, physicist\n* [[Wilhelm Groener]]  (1867\u20131939), German officer and politician\n* [[Caesar von Hofacker]] (1896\u20131944), German Luftwaffe officer and Nazi resistance member, hanged for treason\n* [[Eduard von Kallee]] (1818\u20131888), general, painter und archaeologist\n* [[Richard Kallee]] (1854\u20131933), pastor of [[Stuttgart-Feuerbach]]\n* [[Justinus Kerner]] (1786\u20131862), writer and physician\n* [[Hartmut Michel]] (1948- ), co-recipient of 1988 [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]]\n* [[Eduard M\u00f6rike]] (1804\u20131875), German romantic poet and theologian\n* [[Karl Ludwig von Phull]] (1757\u20131826), general\n* [[Christian Friedrich Daniel Schubart]] (1739\u20131791), poet\n[[File:Christian Friedrich Daniel Schubart.jpg|thumb|150px|Christian Friedrich Daniel Schubart]]\n* [[Tony Schumacher (author)|Tony Schumacher]] (1848\u20131931), author of children's books\n* [[Hugo Sperrle]]  (1885-1953),  German field marshal of the Luftwaffe during World War II.\n* [[David Friedrich Strau\u00df]] (1808\u20131874), theologian and writer\n* [[Albert Veiel]] (1806\u20131874), German dermatologist\n* [[Friedrich Theodor Vischer]] (1807\u20131887), theologian, professor, and politician\n* [[Reinhard von Werneck]] (1757\u20131842), soldier and director of  [[Munich]]'s [[Englischer Garten]]\n* [[Antonio \u010colak]] (born 1993), Croatian footballer who currently plays for [[Darmstadt 98]]\n\n==Twin towns - sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Germany}}\n\nLudwigsburg is [[town twinning|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Partnerst\u00e4dte von Ludwigsburg|url=https://www.ludwigsburg.de/start/stadt_buerger/Partnerstaedte.html|website=ludwigsburg.de|publisher=Ludwigsburg|language=de|accessdate=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Montb\u00e9liard]], France, since 1950\n*{{flagicon|WAL}} [[Caerphilly]], Wales, United Kingdom, since 1960\n*{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Yevpatoria]], Ukraine,  since 1990\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[St. Charles, Missouri|St. Charles]], United States, since 1995\n*{{flagicon|CZE}} [[Nov\u00fd Ji\u010d\u00edn]], Czech Republic, since 1991\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Andrea Hahn: ''Ludwigsburg, Stationen einer Stadt'', Andreas Hackenberg Verlag, Ludwigsburg 2004, {{ISBN|3-937280-02-2}}\n* Gernot von Hahn, Friedhelm Horn: ''Ludwigsburg, Stadt der Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten'', Medien-Verlag Schubert, Stuttgart 1998, {{ISBN|3-929229-55-2}}\n* Bruno Hahnemann: ''Ludwigsburg. Stadt - Schl\u00f6sser - Bl\u00fchendes Barock'', Verlag Ungeheuer + Ulmer, Ludwigsburg 1979\n* on the sidelines, Frederick Forsyth: The Odessa File ({{ISBN|0-553-27198-9}})\n* Annette Weinke, ''Eine Gesellschaft ermittelt gegen sich selbst. Die Geschichte der Zentralen Stelle Ludwigsburg 1958-2008'' (Darmstadt: Wissenschaftliche Buchgesellschaft, 2008).\n* Hans H. P\u00f6schko (Hg.), ''Die Ermittler von Ludwigsburg. Deutschland und die Aufkl\u00e4rung nationalsozialistischer Verbreche''n (Berlin: Metropol 2008).\n* Tobias Herrmann / Gisela M\u00fcller, ''Mitteilungen aus dem Bundesarchiv. Themenheft 2008: Die Au\u00dfenstelle Ludwigsburg'' (Koblenz: Bundesarchiv 2008).\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Ludwigsburg}}\n* [http://www.ludwigsburg.de/servlet/PB/menu/-1_l2/index.html Official website of the City of Ludwigsburg]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100911112704/http: